[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

 {Welcome to the course!   I'm leading Latvian grandmaster Arturs Neiksans and up to this date I've written two courses on Chessable: LTR Reversed Sicilian and LTR Kan Sicilian, both for Black.   This is my third course for Chessable and this time, instead of Lifetime Repertoires, I'm aiming for a more narrow topic - my goal is to explain the concept of King's Indian Attack in a simple and easy-to-understand language.   It's also my first Chessable course for White! The reason why I chose this topic is simple - I've had a vast experience of playing it.   In my childhood, I had a very strong impression from a certain book in the Russian language (I don't remember the title) that nicely illustrated a fascinating system against the French Defense, which for a long time I would call Closed French.   The former World champion Robert James (often referred to as Bobby) Fischer would easily dispatch his opponents in spectacular kingside attacks which inspired me to try it. With the help of King's Indian Attack I've had many memorable games, thus I felt that it's logical to give my respect to Fischer's legacy and also include quite a bit of my experience, playing the system.What makes it truly special is that King's Indian Attack is applicable against a great number of openings - starting with1.e4it works best against French Defense, Sicilian Paulsen, and Caro-Kann. It is possible to play KIA against Sicilian Najdorf or Sicilian with 2...Nc6 but the results won’t be as great. The same applies to Black’s1...e5.After2.Nf3Nc6you can continue with3.d3, followed by Nbd2, g2-g3, and Bg2 but Black gets total freedom in development and has nothing to worry about. I advise you to choose your battles carefully, rather than playing KIA against everything.  If you are starting the game with1.Nf3– KIA works well against most of the popular setups that Black can choose, which are covered in the course. I didn’t cover the Grünfeld or King’s Indian Attack – you can play the KIA in the same manner or choose something more principled that you’re used to. As I already said, it’s not a wonder weapon against every system.This is also the reason why I'm offering lines for both 1.e4 and 1.Nf3 players - everybody will find something interesting. Even if you're not playing the other starting move, I recommend studying all four chapters for a better understanding of the arising positions. The purpose of this system and the course is NOT to build you a complete repertoire - that's why Chessable has many great authors, working on the LTR series. I want to explain the ideas, structures, and directions of the King's Indian Attack - so that you can freely improvise and recognize the best moves with ease.   Not always will there be an advantage, at least according to the chess engines - sometimes engines even might say that White is worse! However, in practical games, a vast majority of players are scared or at least worried about a direct attack against the king, and this is why the King's Indian Attack is such a popular weapon not only at the club level but sometimes at the highest level - think decisive games of FIDE World Cup. The course is divided into 4 theoretical chapters but I've also separated 11 model games and 12 typical structures for better understanding.} 1. Nf3 {I'm starting with the Reti opening as I figured that there's a greater chance that the game will steer into King's Indian against most Black's replies. As I already said before, you can transpose to the King's Indian Attack with 1.e4 as well, should Black choose one of the mentioned defenses. If Black would continue with ...e7-e5, or play Najdorf, King's Indian attack doesn't work so well.1.e4e6(1...c62.Nf3d53.d3This is analyzed in Chapter 4).1...c52.Nf3e63.d3Nc64.g3d55.Nbd2This will transpose to King's Indian Attack.2.d3d53.Nd2Nf64.Ngf3This can very well transpose to King's Indian Attack.} 
1. d5
2. g3 {In the classical sense, the King's Indian attack is considered the following moves - Bg2, O-O, d2-d3, Nbd2, and e2-e4. While not always it is the best approach against every single system, I will try to explain it as simply as I can and briefly mention more challenging alternatives. Your big goal is a kingside attack.} 
2. Nf6 {The most critical continuations will be explained in the course - this is one of the most popular approaches from Black. Black has other reasonable choices as well.} 
3. Bg2
3. e6 {Typical - Black wants to play ...Be7, castle short, and normally anticipates White to play d2-d4, which would steer the game into Catalan.} 
4. O-O
4. Be7
5. d3 {This is the true start of the King's Indian attack. As an alternative, White can switch to Catalan with5.d4, or improvise quite a bit with either5.c4or5.b3.} 
5. O-O
6. Nbd2
6. c5 {By a great margin, the most popular move for Black. Black advanced the c-pawn to fight for the center, followed by the knight move.} 
7. e4
7. Nc6
8. Re1 {White wants to close the center with e4-e5 and start a kingside attack. It's debatable if you want to start with8.e5and avoid some rare sidelines - I like the text move a little bit more due to flexibility by not committing to e4-e5 just yet.} 
