1. e4 {It is possible to reach KIA positions through1.e4, but this depends on Black's response.} 
1. c6
2. Nf3 {Recently, I have become fond of using this move specifically against the Caro-Kann. What makes it even better is that it fits into the schemes of the King's Indian Attack!} 
2. d5
3. d3 {I think this move order is a smart way to avoid one of the best setups that Black can use against the King's Indian Attack. Additionally, White doesn't mind trading queens.} 
3. Bg4 {A pretty standard response from a Caro-Kann player - the idea is to bring out the light-squared bishop and secure the position with ...e7-e6.3...dxe4can be a tempting move for Black, but it might not be the best. After4.dxe4Qxd1+5.Kxd1, it may seem that Black has achieved more since he has no weaknesses while the white king can never castle. However, upon closer inspection of the position, it becomes clear that the king will actually feel safe on c2. Additionally, one of White's other ideas is to move the knight from f3 to e1 with f2-f3 to follow, thus solidifying the position at the kingside while leaving the queenside open for White's use.} 
4. h3
4. Bh5 {If Black takes on f3, White takes with the queen and can then proceed with g2-g3 and Bg2, seeking to open the game for the light-squared bishop in the long-term.The intermezzo move4...dxe4is bad, as after5.hxg4White will enjoy the extra benefits of the open h-file.} 
5. Nc3 {White makes sure that ...dxe4 now doesn't force the queen trade. This is a moment where Black needs to be quite careful, especially if he's not familiar with the nuances of this variation.} 
5. e6 {The most logical move that Black can think of.5...dxe46.Nxe4Consider moves such as Qe2, g2-g4, Bd2, and Bg2 in the upcoming moves. Black lacks typical pressure against White's d-pawn since it stands not on d4, but on d3!5...Nf6The only thing you need to know here is that the immediate move6.e5is not very good, as Black will intermezzo take on f3 and only then retreat with the knight to d7 for a good game. Instead,6.g4!is a better move for White. White has a lot of interesting ideas such as h2-h4-h5 next, placing the knight on e5, or playing a simple Qe2 to secure the center. It might even require a pawn sacrifice.} 
6. g4 {A pretty common way to bother the black bishop.} 
6. Bg6 {6...dxe4White has a number of great moves. The easiest is7.Nxe4Bg68.Qe2with ideas to play either Bd2 or Bf4 and O-O-O. The game could continue with8...h59.g5Ne710.Bf4Nf511.Ne5and White has an advantage. A more adventurous continuation is7.Ne5with similar ideas as in the previous variation -7...Qd48.f4!Bg69.h4. The game is a mess but it’s fun!} 
7. h4 {White wants to capture the bishop with h4-h5.} 
7. dxe4 {7...h58.Ne5Bh79.g5!This is very strong for White - be ready to sacrifice a piece.} 
8. h5 {A truly beautiful move - White sacrifices a pawn for a strong long-term initiative.} 
8. Bxh5 {The best chance for Black is to take immediately on f3. However, the resulting position is more or less the same, and White will need to find another precise move.} 
9. Ne5 {The rest is rather simple.} 
9. Bg6
10. Nxg6
10. fxg6 {Forced! For obvious reasons, Black can't take with the h-pawn.} 
11. Nxe4 {White has excellent compensation for the pawn and Black is struggling to keep together his weaknesses on e6 and h7.} 
