2. d3
2. d5
3. Nd2
3. c5
4. Ngf3
4. Nc6
5. g3 {The actual starting position of the Classical KIA allows for various plans for Black. In addition to the main plan of ...Nf6 and ...Be7 to follow, which you can learn in this Quickstarter with 1.Nf3, Black can also opt to play ...Bd6, followed by ...Nge7, or fianchetto the dark-squared bishop on g7.  In both cases, Black is making good preparations against White's thematic e4-e5 push, challenging the e5 pawn immediately.} 
5. Bd6 {When the bishop is on d6, Black's plan is to follow up with ...Nge7 and castle short. Although this strategy does slow down White's push of e4-e5, it leaves Black's pieces positioned suboptimally for any other active operations in the center or on the queenside.} 
6. Bg2
6. Nge7
7. O-O
7. O-O
8. Re1 {White plays simple and positional chess, hinting towards something active in the center. Here Black has several ways to continue.} 
8. Bc7 {Black wants to meet the standard White's e4-e5 push with ...Ng6, immediately challenging the e-pawn. That's why we're not going to do it.} 
9. c3
9. b6
10. d4 {It is also possible to play10.e5, but in this case, Black has a strong setup to meet it.  Instead, it makes more sense to open up the center with more options to choose from, and possibly aim for isolated queen's pawn (IQP) positions, as Black's piece coordination is far from optimal.  In the IQP, Black's dark-squared bishop belongs on e7 to guard the kingside.} 
10. cxd4
11. Nxd4
11. Nxd4
12. cxd4 {If Black now doesn't take on e4, you can consider to play e4-e5, Nf3, h2-h4 and develop an initiative at the kingside.} 
12. dxe4
13. Nxe4
13. Nd5
14. Qc2 {The general rule of the IQP - don't focus too much on the d-pawn but think about creative ways to get to the black king. White is threatening to play next Ng5.} 
14. Bb7 {14...h6doesn’t solve Black’s problems as after15.Nc3Bb716.Nxd5Bxd517.Bxd5exd518.Qf5White has a serious pressure.} 
15. Ng5
15. g6
16. Ne4 {White has the initiative.} 
