7. O-O {Now Black has a choice of where to position the knight - either f6 or e7.} 
7. Nge7 {Black's idea is to keep a close eye on the e5 square and if necessary, reroute the knight to g6 to challenge it. By the way, it also doesn't close its own dark-squared bishop.} 
8. Re1 {White continues with the traditional plan and is thinking about pushing e4-e5 in a near future. Let's remember what we learned from the main line - if Black doesn't castle short just yet, think twice before you push e4-e5.} 
8. O-O {This should be the most obvious move that Black can choose from. White's idea remains to play e5, but the execution is important.} 
9. c3 {White prepares to play e4-e5, so that it can be strenthened with d3-d4. Black has a few choices.} 
9. b6 {Probably a move that most people will choose in this position - Black activates the light-squared bishop.} 
10. e5
