1. Nf3 {In the course, both1.e4and1.Nf3will be used as starting moves since the focus is on explaining the KIA system. In the Quickstarter, the Reti opening will be used instead, as it is more likely to lead to a King's Indian formation against most Black defenses. While the King's Indian Attack can also be achieved with1.e4against defenses such as the Sicilian Paulsen, French Defense, or Caro-Kann Defense, it may not work as well against other defenses such as1...e5or the Sicilian Najdorf. Therefore, it's important to choose your openings wisely and pick the right battles.} 
1. d5 {Not surprisingly, this is the most frequently played system on online chess platforms against the Reti opening. This system can also be reached by playing1.e4, if Black responds with either the French Defense or Sicilian Paulsen with2...e6.} 
2. g3
2. c6 {The order of the moves may vary, but the underlying ideas in this defense remain the same. Black employs this defense to counter White's plans to fianchetto the bishop on g2, as one of White's key ideas is to play c2-c4 and Qb3, putting pressure on the b7 pawn.   By playing this defense, Black prevents White's pawn advance from creating a chain of pawns (d5-c6-b7), which would reduce the long-distance influence of Black's bishop.} 
3. Bg2 {In this opening, Black has two major options: where to develop the light-squared bishop, either on f5 or g4. Black may also include ...Nf6 immediately or later on, but typically, the same positions are reached with various move orders. Some advanced players may delay the development of the kingside knight and instead first develop the light-squared bishop on g4. After playing ...e7-e6 and ...Bd6, they reserve the option to put the bishop on e7 instead. The idea is that the black knight on f6 may not always be well-placed. However, it's also worth noting that the knight on e7 doesn't always stand well either - there are pros and cons to each option.} 
3. Nf6 {In my opinion, after this move, it would be more sensible to continue with ...Bf5. As I mentioned earlier, after the immediate ...Bg4, there are lines where Black positions the knight on e7 to gain more flexibility. However, this may not be a crucial factor in all variations.} 
4. O-O
4. Bf5 {With the move ...b6, Black has prevented any potential threats of c2-c4 and Qb3, making it an excellent time to bring out the light-squared bishop and solidify the center with ...e7-e6. It's worth noting that playing ...e7-e6 immediately after ...b6 would not make much sense, as it would trap the bishop behind its own pawn chain.} 
5. d3
5. e6
6. Nbd2
6. h6 {This move is often seen in various lines, as it secures the light-squared bishop against potential threats such as Nh4 or e2-e4. By placing the bishop on h7, it becomes untouchable while still being able to operate from the shadows.} 
7. b3 {White fianchettoes the bishop on b2 and is preparing to play e2-e4.} 
7. Be7
8. Bb2
8. O-O
9. Qe1 {White's plan is to play e2-e4 while keeping the rook on f1, as the idea is to launch a kingside attack involving f2-f4 later on. For this reason, the white rook is best placed on e1, which is different from its placement on f1.} 
9. Bh7 {It makes sense for Black to immediately retreat the bishop, as it provides more options for development. By placing the bishop on h7, it becomes untouchable and safer than on g6.} 
10. e4 {White's plan remains to push e4-e5.} 
10. a5 {The most flexible choice that Black has is to play ...d5, which not only immediately fights for the center but also prepares for the possible capture on d5 with the pawn. Black can still opt for both ...Nbd7 or ...Na6 later, or even open the center with ...dxe4 after White captures on d5. Additionally, ...d5 also puts pressure on White's pawn on e4 and potentially opens up Black's light-squared bishop.} 
11. a4 {Probably the simplest choice - White stops Black from advancing.} 
11. Na6 {The black knight jumps to b4 but luckily for us, we can ignore it.} 
12. Qe2
12. Nb4
13. Ne1 {This move is quite picturesque, as White protects the c-pawn and prepares to launch a kingside attack. It puts pressure on Black to figure out how to respond. White's plan is straightforward: avoid playing c2-c3, as it weakens the center and creates vulnerabilities on important squares, despite seeming to gain a tempo.} 
13. Nd7
14. f4 {White's game is simpler with a lot of improvising at the kingside.} 
