3. Bg2 {In this opening, Black has two major options: where to develop the light-squared bishop, either on f5 or g4. Black may also include ...Nf6 immediately or later on, but typically, the same positions are reached with various move orders. Some advanced players may delay the development of the kingside knight and instead first develop the light-squared bishop on g4. After playing ...e7-e6 and ...Bd6, they reserve the option to put the bishop on e7 instead. The idea is that the black knight on f6 may not always be well-placed. However, it's also worth noting that the knight on e7 doesn't always stand well either - there are pros and cons to each option.} 
3. Bg4
4. h3 {Before defining White's plan, it's often useful to play h2-h3. In some lines where Black takes on f3 after White plays e2-e4, this move order can gain a tempo. Additionally, the bishop on h5 may become a target with White's g3-g4 and f2-f4, so retreating it early can be beneficial. If Black takes on f3 immediately, White has several options for recapturing, such as with the bishop, which allows for flexible choices in the center with moves like d2-d4 and c2-c4 or d2-d3 and e2-e4. Another interesting option is to play exf3, which opens up the f-file and can create dynamic possibilities for both sides.} 
4. Bh5 {Retreating to h5 and keeping the tension in the center is logical.4...Bxf3. If Black captures on f3 immediately, there's an interesting idea that I want to suggest:5.exf3!?Of course, there's nothing wrong with capturing with the bishop and then trying to open the position for the bishop pair with something like c2-c4 or e2-e4, but this move is really idea-based and rather unpleasant for Black, especially if it comes as a surprise.5...Nd7. White gives another chance for Black to play ...e7-e5.6.O-O. A careful move - now that Black has traded the light-squared bishop, it's a good idea to build a brick wall.6...e67.d3. The most flexible idea - White wants to play next f3-f4, bring the knight to f3, followed by such moves as Be3, c2-c3, and push forward the a-pawn. It is possible to play d2-d4 immediately, but then you lose some flexibility, including closing the bishop's diagonal on e3. Also, the pawn on d4 at some point could become a target of Black's counterplay with ...c6-c5.7...Ngf68.f4Bd6. A logical idea as Black also keeps an option at some point later to play ...e6-e5.9.Nd2O-O10.Nf3a5. While this maneuver in the position is quite common to fight for the space advantage at the queenside, the real question that Black needs to answer is whether to push ...e6-e5 or not. If Black does it, the position opens, and White simply enjoys a slightly better position due to the bishop pair. Remember the early choice to take on f3 with the e-pawn and not the bishop? Already then, you were thinking about how to improve the light-squared bishop power later in the game. Here it's already becoming stronger as Black weakens the control of the center.11.a4. You can also ignore the a-pawn's march, but I think that in general, it doesn't hurt to fight for a space advantage when you can.11...Qc712.Re1Rfe813.Be3Re714.c3. All of these moves are pretty common for the position. If Black wants to have some counterplay, he has to push ...e6-e5 now, accepting a slightly worse position.14...Rae815.d4. Change of scenery - with a2-a4 and ...a7-a5 included, now Black can't easily seek the counterplay with ...c6-c5 as the b5 square would be weakened for good. Think about moving your knight or even the light-squared bishop there! This move was already available a move before.To gain a deeper understanding of this line, you can explore it further in the theoretical chapter.} 
5. d3
5. Nd7
6. O-O
6. Ngf6
7. Qe1 {Another option for White is to play7.Nbd2, developing a piece and avoiding the x-ray from Black's light-squared bishop. This move prepares for an active play in the center and usually followed by e2-e4. However, there's also a surprise element to this move that can keep Black guessing.} 
7. e5 {The most logical move - Black also can be ambitious.} 
8. e4
8. dxe4 {The safe move - Black closes the center to avoid any potential x-ray problems from the white queen, which conveniently stands on the same file as the black king.} 
9. dxe4 {Now it depends on Black's move. If Black develops the dark-squared bishop to e7, it's best for White to develop the queenside knight to c4, strengthening it with a2-a4. The kingside knight can be activated via h4-f5, while also considering the aggressive f2-f4 pawn push.} 
9. Bc5 {Some may argue against developing the bishop humbly on e7 when it was previously active on c5. However, the reality is that developing the bishop to e7 can be a more practical choice as it avoids losing a tempo later on.} 
10. a4 {This move is quite common and serves two purposes for White. Firstly, it gains space on the queenside, which can limit Black's counterplay in that area. Secondly, it can also prevent Black from playing ...-a5-a4, which would undermine White's pawn structure.} 
10. O-O {At some point, Black may consider taking on f3, aiming for a position with two knights as the light-squared bishop on h5 can potentially become a target or just become passive. However, it's important to remember the purpose of the early h2-h3 move. If Black takes on f3 after already having retreated to h5, they acknowledge the tempo loss, which is always beneficial for White.} 
11. Nbd2
11. Re8
12. Nb3
12. Bf8
13. Nh4 {These maneuvers are quite common - the kingside knight heads to f5, aiming to put pressure on Black's position, while the dark-squared bishop finds a good square on e3. While there may not be any immediate advantage for White, these are strong and flexible moves that can lead to a good positional game.} 
