1. Nf3 {In the course, both1.e4and1.Nf3will be used as starting moves since the focus is on explaining the KIA system. In the Quickstarter, the Reti opening will be used instead, as it is more likely to lead to a King's Indian formation against most Black defenses. While the King's Indian Attack can also be achieved with1.e4against defenses such as the Sicilian Paulsen, French Defense, or Caro-Kann Defense, it may not work as well against other defenses such as1...e5or the Sicilian Najdorf. Therefore, it's important to choose your openings wisely and pick the right battles.} 
1. d5 {Not surprisingly, this is the most frequently played system on online chess platforms against the Reti opening. This system can also be reached by playing1.e4, if Black responds with either the French Defense or Sicilian Paulsen with2...e6.} 
2. g3
2. Nf6
3. Bg2
3. e6 {There's a good reason why this approach is so popular for Black - he aims for a quick short castle and is pretty flexible with the choices later. The only minor drawback - the light-squared bishop is slightly passive but often it's moved to the a8-h1 diagonal.} 
4. O-O
4. Be7
5. d3 {The start of King's Indian attack. White's plan is pretty simple - aim for a kingside attack which will start with closing the center. Black soon will be at crossroads.} 
5. c5 {The classical way to continue to fight for the central squares. Of course, Black can also immediately castle or be a little tricky. Very often these lines are highly transpositional and the order of the moves can change.5...b6This early maneuver to fianchetto Black's light-squared bishop on b7 so early means only one thing - Black wants to discourage you to play e2-e4.6.Nbd2Bb77.e4!Yet White can still play it!7...dxe4If Black doesn't take the pawn, White can carry out the typical plans of KIA.8.dxe4O-OThe pawn is poisoned due to the pin on the long diagonal.9.Qe2I suggest you pay extra attention, to when to push e4-e5 and when not. While pushing the e-pawn does give White some extra space advantage with a tempo, but it also opens Black's bishop on b7.9...Nc6Black's ...c7-c5 here seems to be useless since he already traded the d-pawn.10.Rd110.c3also looks nice to limit Black's knight on c6.10...Qc811.b3Why not? The white bishop on b2 stands pretty well.11...a512.Bb2!White ignores Black's threat to push ... a5-a4 - make sure you remember the following idea!12...a413.a3!An unusual idea!13...axb314.cxb3Black has wasted a couple of tempos and achieved nothing. Black is pretty much cramped and would love to trade some pieces but it is easier said than done.} 
6. Nbd2
6. Nc6
7. e4 {Let's stop here for a moment to understand, where the game is heading. White wants to launch a kingside attack and AFTER Black castles short, close the center with e4-e5. After all, the rule 'the best way to counter an attack at either the kingside or queenside with a swift counter-attack in the center' has been around forever, thus take away this option from your opponent. Black here has three major choices: 1) Ignore White's threats, castle short, and focus on storming at the queenside with an aggressive pawn push. Engines like this approach the most, also all chess professionals know it by heart but in a practical game not everything is so obvious! 2) Avoid short castling for the moment to anticipate White's incoming e4-e5 and keep an option to castle long. 3) Stop White from playing e4-e5 at all - this in general is not good.} 
7. Qc7 {The black queen often stands on c7 to apply extra pressure against the vital e5 square but with this order of the moves Black might be planning something trickier.} 
8. Re1
8. b6 {If this happens, I suggest you be alert! Notice that Black doesn't castle short and instead of the aggressive ...b7-b5-b4 pawn push plays the modest ...b7-b6. What could be the idea here?} 
9. Qe2 {The order of the moves here perhaps is not so important but the two principles are: 1) Keep the tension in the center until Black castles short. Be ready to rip apart the queenside if Black castles the long way. 2) Try to exploit the black queen's placement on c7 with Bf4.} 
9. Bb7
10. c3 {This is a good waiting move, taking extra control of some of the critical squares and also limiting the black knight on c6. Not always it's a preparation move for e5 and d4, as you may have seen in some French defense lines.} 
10. h6 {A standard useful move for Black in these positions, thinking about ...g7-g5 at some point later.} 
11. Nf1
11. d4 {If Black wants to castle long, it's logical to attempt to close the center. Don't miss Black's intentions to play ...e6-e5 next, thus fortifying his control of the center.} 
12. e5 {White stops Black's attempt to close the center with ...e6-e5.} 
12. Nd7
13. h4 {White slows down Black's idea to play ...g7-g5 and is ready to reroute the knight from f1 to g4. This line is quite familiar to one of the previous sidelines where Black would play ...Qc7 with intentions to castle long, except here is a major difference - Black has committed himself to ...d5-d4. This means, castling long is by no means an obvious decision as White will very quickly open the queenside.} 
13. O-O-O {For the sake of argument, let's check what happens if Black does continue with the plan. If Black would rush with ... g7-g5 before castling, you can safely take the pawn. Black's attack is not ready.} 
14. N1h2 {The white knight typically is heading to g4, where it also stops Black's g-pawn advancement.} 
14. Kb8
15. a3 {A good move to remind Black of the consequences castling long.} 
15. g5 {Now that the black king is gone from the center, Black can attempt to break through the kingside but the best part is - White doesn't have to comply!} 
16. h5 {A great idea to know! White closes the kingside and is about to move his knight to g4, securing the kingside, while the queenside attack looks quite real.} 
