7. e4 {Let's stop here for a moment to understand, where the game is heading. White wants to launch a kingside attack and AFTER Black castles short, close the center with e4-e5.   After all, the rule 'the best way to counter an attack at either the kingside or queenside with a swift counter-attack in the center' has been around forever, thus take away this option from your opponent.   Black here has three major choices:   1) Ignore White's threats, castle short, and focus on storming at the queenside with an aggressive pawn push - this is going to be the main line of the chapter. Engines like this approach the most, also all chess professionals know it by heart but in a practical game not everything is so obvious!   2) Avoid short castling for the moment to anticipate White's incoming e4-e5 and keep an option to castle long.   3) Stop White from playing e4-e5 at all - this in general is not good.} 
7. O-O
8. Re1 {White continues with the plan - now that Black has castled short, the idea is to push e4-e5, close the center and focus on the kingside. Technically, it's possible to play it immediately but Black might force you to position the queen on e2 to protect the e5 pawn. Best prepare it, plus White is also not entirely revealing his cards.} 
8. Qc7 {With the black king already castled short, with the current order of the moves this is a minor inaccuracy as it does not quite stop White's intentions to push e5 as Black can't run with the king towards the queenside. However, you could get there with a transposition of the moves. Because of the black queen's placement on c7, I'd like to show you a couple of tricks that are now available to you.} 
9. Nf1 {This is the idea that with the black queen on c7 I like the most - White wants to win a tempo. There's a good chance that Black won't pay attention to the order of the moves and will walk past the best move quite easily.} 
9. dxe4 {Apparently, the best continuation! It's by no means obvious as normally this is not a good move, plus it drastically changes the pawn structure.} 
10. dxe4
10. Rd8
11. Qe2
11. Nd4 {It could be difficult for Black to understand, why this is the best move - it forms some pressure on the c2 pawn.} 
12. Nxd4
12. cxd4
13. e5 {White carries out the typical idea anyway. Don't allow Black to play ... e6-e5 himself as then all of White's pieces will be positioned awkward.} 
13. Nd5
14. a3 {Probably the simplest approach - White stops the ...Nb4 idea for good and is ready to start a kingside attack with Be4 and Qg4. You can follow one of the model games to get good understanding, in which direction the game might continue. Amin,B (2680)-Pichot,A (2625) Abu Dhabi Masters rapid 2021.} 
