[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. Nf3
1. d5 {In the first chapter, we're going to examine the most popular system that Black can choose. Not surprisingly, it's also the most played system in online chess platforms against the Reti. As I already said in the Introduction, you can get here with1.e4as well, if your opponent plays either the French defense or Sicilian Paulsen with2...e6.} 
2. g3 {The King's Indian attack is a branch of the Reti opening. In case you're looking towards more improvisation later to include moves like c2-c4 or b2-b3, you can focus on it to broaden your understanding of the arising positions.} 
2. Nf6
3. Bg2
3. e6 {There's a good reason why this approach is so popular for Black - he aims for a quick short castle and is pretty flexible with the choices later. The only minor drawback - the light-squared bishop is slightly passive but often it's moved to the a8-h1 diagonal.} 
4. O-O
4. Be7
5. d3 {White's plan is pretty simple - aim for a kingside attack which will start with closing the center. Black soon will be at crossroads.} 
5. c5 {The classical way to continue to fight for the central squares. Of course, Black can also immediately castle or be a little tricky. Very often these lines are highly transpositional and the order of the moves can change.} 
6. Nbd2
6. Nc6
7. e4 {Let's stop here for a moment to understand, where the game is heading. White wants to launch a kingside attack and AFTER Black castles short, close the center with e4-e5.   After all, the rule 'the best way to counter an attack at either the kingside or queenside with a swift counter-attack in the center' has been around forever, thus take away this option from your opponent.   Black here has three major choices:   1) Ignore White's threats, castle short, and focus on storming at the queenside with an aggressive pawn push - this is going to be the main line of the chapter. Engines like this approach the most, also all chess professionals know it by heart but in a practical game not everything is so obvious!   2) Avoid short castling for the moment to anticipate White's incoming e4-e5 and keep an option to castle long.   3) Stop White from playing e4-e5 at all - this in general is not good.} 
7. O-O
8. Re1 {White continues with the plan - now that Black has castled short, the idea is to push e4-e5, close the center and focus on the kingside. Technically, it's possible to play it immediately but Black might force you to position the queen on e2 to protect the e5 pawn. Best prepare it, plus White is also not entirely revealing his cards.} 
8. b5 {Black should immediately go for an aggressive pawn storm at the queenside. This is also the best response according to the chess engines but for humans, it's quite difficult to remain calm by watching, what White is up to at the kingside!} 
9. e5
9. Nd7
10. Nf1 {White's plan is pretty much always the same - that's why it makes such a popular weapon!} 
10. a5 {If you say A, might say B as well.} 
11. h4 {I believe that playing h2-h4 early is important because sometimes early committing to Bf4 can run into the surprising ...g7-g5-g4 and White loses the e5 pawn.   Consider this - since Black did not position his queen on c7 to pressure the e5 pawn, perhaps you can skip Bf4 to save a tempo? Food for thought.   Either way, here Black has plenty of options - he can either continue pushing forward the queenside pawns and hope that something good will happen, or in some way prevent White's actions at the kingside.} 
11. b4 {One of the main ideas for Black is to push forward the queenside pawns, but with which pawn to start?   There are nuances, that you might simply ignore, but at least consider them. With Black starting the push with ...b5-b4, you might have access to the typical c2-c4 countershot, trying to close down the queenside. However, it contradicts with the philosophy of the entire line - you don't want to open the queenside too much as this is where your opponent is seeking his counterplay.   You're supposed to attack at the kingside, remember? However, under certain circumstances, there might be good exceptions.} 
12. Bf4 {White fortifies the center and doesn't reveal the chosen setup just yet.12.N1h2We can debate about the best order of the moves - White might consider saving a tempo for Bf4 but then again the white knight might not always go to h2. Probably the difference is so tiny that it doesn't matter.} 
12. a4 {Black wants to play ...a4-a3 and create a long-term weakness on c3 - best stop it.} 
13. a3 {Necessary.13.N1h2a314.b3Na7!This is the position that you want to avoid. Albeit the queenside is closed, White's attack at the kingside does not grant you success, but the weaknesses at the queenside are there to stay and might haunt you in the second half of the game.} 
13. bxa3
14. bxa3 {Normally, White recaptures with the pawn and wants to keep things at the queenside closed but since this position can vary and there are many very similar scenarios, keep an eye open for Rxa3, as long as it doesn't jump under the ...c5-c4 threat. This position has been met in practice many times.} 
14. Ba6 {A logical follow-up as there's no better placement for the light-squared bishop, plus the ...c5-c4 threat to open the queenside is always in the air.14...Na5Check one of the model games in this line by Bobby Fischer!} 
15. N1h2 {White doesn't rush with h4-h5 just yet and for the time being keeps control of the g5 square. If Black will rush with ...d5-d4 to put the knight on d5, this might open White the option to play Ng5-Qh5. Immediately it's not as good as Black will have the defensive ...Nd4 maneuver.} 
15. Rb8 {A multi-purpose move - Black keeps all options open and for the moment simply takes over the b-file. Black is also waiting for White to play Ng4 so that he can continue with ...Nd4 to take away from White one of his attacking pieces. If this happens and White trades the knight on d4 to ruin Black's pawn structure, then the knight from g4 takes away some important squares for the white queen, plus it also can't immediately challenge the black d-pawn. Nuances!} 
16. h5
16. h6 {The white pawn has to be stopped, otherwise White will create permanent dark square weaknesses around the black king. Here White once again has two potential plans - either play Ng4 and threaten with a sacrifice on h6, or push the g-pawn to expose the black king.} 
17. Ng4 {White is toying with several ideas - either sacrifice the knight on h6 in one of the next several moves or include c2-c4 at some point to spice up things at the queenside. The black pawn on a4 actually can make a legitimate target.} 
17. Nd4 {With the white knight on g4, this seems to be good timing for Black to play ...Nd4.} 
18. Nxd4 {Seems to be necessary, otherwise Black will reroute his knight on f5 and you can forget about any sacrifices on h6.} 
18. cxd4 {The black d-pawn looks weak but Black's strategy is based on getting to the weak white a3 pawn, thus creating a dangerous passed pawn.} 
19. Nh2 {Quite an odd move! White steps back to create a path to the white queen, while the knight itself will be heading to f3 to challenge the d4 pawn. At some point later, the g-pawn push might become a reality.} 
19. Qc7
20. Ra2 {Another oddity - White locks down the queenside and throws away the key! If you look more closely at the position, for Black it's difficult to find a way to crash through at the queenside, while White can improvize with things at the kingside.} 
20. Rb6
21. Bxd5 {There's quite a fresh online rapid game between two chess legends to give you some extra ideas!} 
21. exd5 {Actually, the almighty engines ignore the bishop and offer to play 21...Rfb8 with the ...Rb2 threat and go after the a3 pawn.} 
22. e6
22. Bd6
23. Bxd6
23. Qxd6
24. exd7
24. Qxd7
25. Qa1 {White's position feels a little shaky but you can't deny that the black d-pawn looks so sweet!} 
25. Qf5
26. Qxd4
26. Re6
27. Raa1 {White consolidated his position and claimed an advantage.} 
27. Qxh5
28. Rxe6
28. fxe6
29. Re1
29. Qf7
30. Ng4
30. Bb5
31. Ne5 {The game between Leko,P   (2663)-Wang,H (2722) Chess.com Global Championship 2022 ended with a dramatic draw, although White is better due to the amazing knight on e5.} 
