8. Re1 {White continues with the traditional plan and is thinking about pushing e4-e5 in a near future. Let's remember what we learned from the main line - if Black doesn't castle short just yet, think twice before you push e4-e5.} 
8. b6 {This move already should signal you that Black is refraining from castling short and that pushing e4-e5 here could be a little early.} 
9. c3 {White is preparing to play either e4-e5, or d3-d4 - it reallly depends on what Black will play.} 
9. Bb7 {If Black continues traditionally, then you can carry out the typical idea.} 
10. e5
10. Qc7
11. d4 {Even if Black decides to castle long, this looks risky for him as White nicely controls the kingside and can improvise quite a bit with the queenside. When entering such positions, make sure that Black has no immediate way to exploit the b4 square at the queenside.} 
11. cxd4
12. cxd4
12. Nb4 {Since the black king is still in the center, this is a mistake.} 
13. Qa4+
13. Nec6
14. Bf1 {White will push back the intruder with a3 and secure a large advantage, mainly due to the dark-square weaknesses at the kingside.} 
