1. e4 {There are a few other systems from Black's perspective that I'd like to talk about and that's the reason why in this chapter I'll be starting with the 1.e4 move. If you are strictly a 1.Nf3 player, the odds that your games will transpose to one of the covered systems in this chapter, are pretty low. However, the extra ideas shouldn't hurt you and I strongly recommend studying it nevertheless!1.Nf3d52.g3(2...c53.Bg2Nc6Then there's this order of the moves - normally Black wants to play ...e7-e5 next, forcing White to play King's Indian with colors reversed. Hardcore King's Indian structure fans probably will be happy to play the same system with both colors, but let me be honest here - White is already slightly worse right out of the opening while Black grabs the center and is very flexible with his choices.4.O-O(By the way, here White's best response is4.d4which is reversed Gruenfeld's defense but that would steer the game away from KIA).4...e6But okay - theoretically Black can opt for something less ambitious as well.5.d3Bd66.Nbd2Nge77.e4We got to one of the critical positions, covered in the chapter but how real is it to get there with 1.Nf3?)2...Nf63.Bg2e64.d3To get to the final position, we'll be starting with4.d3and not castling short, giving Black an idea that White is aiming for the King's Indian attack.4...g6If White had castled short first, Black's choice to play both ...e7-e6 and ...g7-g6 would feel rather weird. Here at least Black is recognizing White's setup and is countering it.5.Nbd2Bg76.e4c57.O-ONc68.Re1And we got to another critical position of the chapter. You'll probably agree, it's easier to get there with 1.e4.} 
1. e6 {1...c5As already explained in the introduction, also Sicilian Paulsen can lead to the same positions.2.Nf3e63.d3d54.Nbd2Now Black can opt for either ...Bd6-Nge7 setup or ...g7-g6 and Bg7.} 
2. d3
2. d5
3. Nd2
3. c5
4. Ngf3
4. Nc6
5. g3 {The actual starting position - in this chapter we will examine two setups from Black, anticipating King's Indian attack from White. One idea is to play ...Bd6, followed by ...Nge7, and the second is fianchetto the dark-squared bishop on g7. In both occasions, Black is making the best possible preparations against White's thematic e4-e5 push, challenging the e5 pawn immediately.} 
5. g6 {Black fianchettoes the bishop on g7 to increase its power and also directly combat the critical e5 square. This, however, comes at a price - he seriously weakens the dark squares around his king. This is what we will base our strategy on. Also, this line can transpose from something else - if Black had fianchettoed the bishop before and only now or a move later played ...d7-d5.} 
6. Bg2
6. Bg7
7. O-O {Now Black has a choice, where to position the knight - either f6 or e7.} 
7. Nge7 {Black's idea is to keep a close eye on the e5 square and if necessary, reroute the knight to g6 to challenge it. By the way, it also doesn't close its own dark-squared bishop.} 
8. Re1 {White continues with the traditional plan and is thinking about pushing e4-e5 in a near future. Let's remember what we learned from the main line - if Black doesn't castle short just yet, think twice before you push e4-e5.} 
8. b6 {This move already should signal you that Black is refraining from castling short and that pushing e4-e5 here could be a little early.} 
9. c3 {White is preparing to play either e4-e5, or d3-d4 - it reallly depends on what Black will play.} 
9. Qc7 {We can arrive at this position with a transposition of moves as well, had Black played ...Qc7 immediately.} 
10. d4 {Luckily for White, the plan remains the same!} 
10. cxd4 {Just to mention, if Black captures on d4 immediately, there's this nice nuance that it's best to take on d4 with the knight to avoid a bad IQP setup.} 
11. Nxd4
11. Nxd4
12. cxd4 {The point is, the black king is a little more exposed, and so is the h1-a8 diagonal. You want to play next e4-e5 and Nf3.} 
12. Bxd4
13. Qa4+
13. Nc6
14. exd5 {Obviously, Black can't do this.} 
