7. Nge7 {Black's idea is to keep a close eye on the e5 square and if necessary, reroute the knight to g6 to challenge it. By the way, it also doesn't close its own dark-squared bishop.} 
8. Re1 {White continues with the traditional plan and is thinking about pushing e4-e5 in a near future. Let's remember what we learned from the main line - if Black doesn't castle short just yet, think twice before you push e4-e5.} 
8. O-O {This should be the most obvious move that Black can choose from.White's idea remains to play e5, but the execution is important.} 
9. c3 {White prepares to play e4-e5, so that it can be strengthened with d3-d4. Black has a few choices.} 
9. b6 {Probably a move that most people will choose in this position - Black activates the light-squared bishop.} 
10. e5
10. Qc7
11. Qe2 {The critical position of the variation.} 
11. g5 {Once again, Black has to go for the following idea, otherwise White's kingside attack will become too strong.} 
12. Nxg5
12. Qxe5
13. Nde4 {We have already looked at this idea - it works also here since the h1-a8 diagonal is weakened.} 
13. dxe4 {Berry, S (2335) - Gershon, A (2510) Dresden 2003. In the game, White got lost in the complications. He played14.Qh5?h615.Bf4Qf616.Bxe4e517.Nh7Qd6and eventually could not reclaim the sacrificed material since the knight on h7 is doomed.} 
14. Bf4 {The better way of playing this position!} 
14. Qf6
15. Bxe4
15. e5
16. Bxh7+ {It appears to be stronger than taking with the knight.} 
16. Kh8
17. Qh5
17. Bg4
18. Qxg4
18. exf4
19. Be4 {White has very good compensation for the sacrificed piece - there's the threat of Nh7, and also the third pawn on f4 is under attack. This transposes to something that you have already seen before.} 
