[White "3) 1.Nf3: Black's ...d5 + ...c6/...Bf5/...Bg4"]
[Black "1.Nf3 d5 2.g3 c6 3.Bg2 Nf6 #1"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. Nf3
1. d5
2. g3
2. c6 {In this chapter we will focus on one of the most popular systems, if Black plays ...d7-d5 and strengthens the center with ...c7-c6. The order of the moves can vary but the ideas always remain the same. Black plays it to combat White's plans to fianchetto the bishop on g2 as after Bg2 one of White's ideas is to play c2-c4 and Qb3, challenging the b7 pawn. Now it will gaze against a chain of pawns (d5-c6-b7), thus reducing its long-distance influence.2...Nf6I couldn't walk past not mentioning yet another game by Bobby Fischer when he was only 14 years old! While this game doesn't directly contribute to the theory, it's good to know some extra ideas.3.Bg2Bf54.O-Oe65.d3Check the model game!} 
3. Bg2 {Here Black has two major choices - he needs to decide, where to develop the light-squared bishop, either on f5 or g4. He might include ...Nf6 immediately or at some point later, but usually, we arrive at the same positions with various move orders.   Some advanced players delay the development of the kingside knight and first develop the light-squared bishop on g4, and then after ...e7-e6, ...Bd6 reserve an option to put it on e7. The idea - not always the black knight on f6 stands well. There's another side of the coin - not always the black knight stands well on e7 as well!} 
3. Nf6 {The way I see it, after this move it makes more sense to continue with ...Bf5 because remember what I said - after the immediate ...Bg4, there are lines when Black positions the knight on e7 for more flexibility. Perhaps it doesn't matter.} 
4. O-O
4. Bf5 {Black has secured himself against any c2-c4 and Qb3 ideas thus it's a perfect moment to bring out the light-squared bishop and solidify the center with ...e7-e6. Which, by the way, immediately would not make any sense as that would imprison the bishop.} 
5. d3
5. e6
6. Nbd2
6. h6 {You might see this move in these lines quite often - the idea is to secure the light-squared bishop against any Nh4 or e2-e4 ideas. On h7 the black bishop is untouchable while still operating from the shadows.} 
7. b3 {This idea was very popular in the 60-ties and 70-ties and I see no good reason, why it wouldn't work also today! White fianchettos the bishop on b2 and is preparing to play e2-e4.} 
7. Be7
8. Bb2
8. Nbd7 {If Black for some reason delays castling short, you can immediately push e2-e4 and save one tempo for Qe1! If Black takes on e4, the g7 pawn hangs.} 
9. e4
9. Bg4 {Also after9...Bh7White can continue in the same manner of pushing e4-e5.} 
10. h3
10. Bh5
11. e5 {The black knight has no good retreat squares.} 
11. Nh7
12. Qe1 {White dodges the pin with the usual maneuver and prepares to play next Nd4 and f2-f4.12...g5!?It makes sense for Black to complicate the game.13.Nd4This maneuver you might have already seen before. White prepares to push forward the f-pawn.13...Qc714.f4gxf415.gxf4Rg816.f5Perhaps a little hasty - White could have started with16.c4to remind Black that castling long can have serious consequences.16...Bc5?Black had to castle long.17.Kh1Bxd418.Bxd4O-O-O19.Qh4Now Black inevitably loses material.19...c520.Bg1Be221.Rf2Qxe522.Re1White quickly won the game in Neiksans, A (2590)-Ocko, D (1913) European Rapid Championship 2017.} 
