4. O-O
4. Bf5 {Black has secured himself against any c2-c4 and Qb3 ideas thus it's a perfect moment to bring out the light-squared bishop and solidify the center with ...e7-e6. Which, by the way, immediately would not make any sense as that would imprison the bishop.} 
5. d3
5. e6
6. Nbd2
6. h6 {You might see this move in these lines quite often - the idea is to secure the light-squared bishop against any Nh4 or e2-e4 ideas. On h7 the black bishop is untouchable while still operating from the shadows.} 
7. b3 {This idea was very popular in the 60-ties and 70-ties and I see no good reason, why it wouldn't work also today! White fianchettos the bishop on b2 and is preparing to play e2-e4.} 
7. Be7
8. Bb2
8. O-O
9. Qe1 {That's the move that I like the most! My inspiration was such chess legends as Lev Polugaevsky and Viktor Korchnoi who would play this system back in the 60-ties and 70-ties, along with other well-known names. White wants to play e2-e4 but keep the rook on f1 as the idea is to go for the kingside attack which will involve a later f2-f4. That's essentially the difference with the first chapter, where White would develop his dark-squared bishop on f4, followed by h2-h4-h5. There the white rook best belongs on e1 - I hope you understand the difference!} 
9. Bh7 {For Black, it makes sense to retreat with the bishop immediately as then he has more options to choose from. On h7 the bishop is untouchable, unlike the g6 square.} 
10. e4 {Now Black has some choices, on how to react. White's plan remains to push e4-e5.} 
10. dxe4 {Since the black bishop controls the b1-h7 diagonal, it's a reasonable idea for Black to take on e4 as it will make White's plan of pushing e4-e5 not a strong as with the center closed.} 
11. dxe4 {The trick here is that the e-pawn push for White is no longer recommended as it would open Black's bishop on h7 and also starting a successful kingside attack with the center wide open does not seem to be likely. However, White can adapt and play positional chess, where the black bishop on h7 perhaps is simply shut out from the game, as it's staring at the e4 pawn.} 
11. Nbd7 {If Black plays it out a little more modestly, watch the following plan for White.} 
12. Qe2
12. Qc7
13. Rfd1
13. Rfd8
14. Ne1 {White improves the knight to d3 and if necessary, can close Black's bishop on h7 permanently with f2-f3, if the situation requires it.} 
14. Nc5
15. Nd3
15. Nxd3
16. cxd3 {White has a great position out of the opening - Black's bishop on h7 feels quite useless.} 
