10. Nbd7 {Black needs to answer himself, where to position the queenside knight - either on d7 or on a6. On d7 Black's position in general seems to be quite compact and solid, but the knight takes away a potential retreat square for the other knight.} 
11. Qe2 {There's no need to rush with the e4-e5 push as perhaps Black will play something drastic when having some extra tension in the center will benefit White. Here Qe2 is a typical maneuver as it improves the control of the central squares and also connects the rooks.} 
11. a5 {Of course, the position is quite transpositional - Black can still take on e4 at any given moment, reaching a position that we already discussed. If that happens, just remember the general rule - you don't want to push e5 anymore as it would open Black's light-squared bishop.} 
