10. e4 {Now Black has some choices, on how to react. White's plan remains to push e4-e5.} 
10. a5 {The most flexible choice that Black has - he's threatening with ...a5-a4, causing some annoyances at the queenside while can still opt for both ...Nbd7 or ...Na6 or even open the center with ...dxe4.} 
11. a4 {Probably the simplest choice - White stops Black's advancing. Let me point out here an interesting detail - you can play also11.a3, which would seem a little more cautious as it does not give away the b4 square for the black knight.However, the problem, in general, is that in that pawn structure one of Black's strongest ideas is to play ...c6-c5 and then threaten with ...a5-a4, or start with ...Qb6, followed by ...a5-a4, White's b3-b4 and Black's ...c6-c5 - then White's queenside starts to feel rather vulnerable. Engines even go as far as starting with 11.a3 and then, depending on how Black continues, for example ...Nbd7 or ...c6-c5, willingly loses a tempo and plays now a3-a4!   The idea is rather paradoxical and I didn't want to suggest something so weird but it's a good extra idea for you to think about - sometimes losing a tempo is not a bad thing, because all that matters is the position as a whole. The text move still is much simpler.} 
11. Na6 {The black knight jumps to b4 but luckily for us, we can ignore it.} 
12. Qe2
12. Nb4
13. Ne1 {Quite a picture-esque move - White protects the c-pawn and is about to move forward with everything he has at the kingside. It's not easy for Black to understand, what to do. White's plan is very straightforward. Don't play c2-c3, as it would weaken your center and also some of the most important squares, even if it may seem to win a tempo.} 
13. Nd7
14. f4 {White's game is simpler with a lot of improvising at the kingside.14.c3?Tempting but now you see that your dark-squared bishop on b2 is blocked by the pawn and you have created weaknesses on b3 and d3 for no good reason14...Na6.14.f4Bf6?!This is how the game continued - Black decided to force White's hand and provoked him to close the center, not realizing that it's part of the plan.15.e5Be716.g4Re817.Kh1f6A typical human response - counter-attack where you are being attacked.18.Ndf3fxe519.Nxe5Nxe520.Bxe5Quite similarly as in one of the previous Korchnoi's games, Polugaevsky secures thee5square as a great outpost for one of the minor pieces.20...c521.Rd1Nc622.Nf3Nxe523.Nxe5White had a solid advantage in Polugaevsky, L - Addison, W Palma de Mallorca Interzonal 1970.} 
