1. Nf3
1. d5
2. g3
2. c6 {In this chapter we will focus on one of the most popular systems, if Black plays ...d7-d5 and strengthens the center with ...c7-c6. The order of the moves can vary but the ideas always remain the same. Black plays it to combat White's plans to fianchetto the bishop on g2 as after Bg2 one of White's ideas is to play c2-c4 and Qb3, challenging the b7 pawn. Now it will gaze against a chain of pawns (d5-c6-b7), thus reducing its long-distance influence.2...Nf6I couldn't walk past not mentioning yet another game by Bobby Fischer when he was only 14 years old! While this game doesn't directly contribute to the theory, it's good to know some extra ideas.3.Bg2Bf54.O-Oe65.d3Check the model game!} 
3. Bg2 {Here Black has two major choices - he needs to decide, where to develop the light-squared bishop, either on f5 or g4. He might include ...Nf6 immediately or at some point later, but usually, we arrive at the same positions with various move orders.   Some advanced players delay the development of the kingside knight and first develop the light-squared bishop on g4, and then after ...e7-e6, ...Bd6 reserve an option to put it on e7. The idea - not always the black knight on f6 stands well. There's another side of the coin - not always the black knight stands well on e7 as well!} 
3. Bg4 {3...g64.d3Bg75.Nbd2This transposes to the positions in Chapter 4. Of course, you can toy with the order of the moves.} 
4. h3 {I loved this move many years ago even before the engines did and I discovered it on my own!   The idea is quite tricky - you play h2-h3 before defining White's plan. At some point later in the line (after White pushes e2-e4), Black takes on f3 to solidify the control of the center.   If you include h2-h3 early, then after the retreat on h5, Black essentially loses a tempo, if he will want to take on f3 later! The bishop on h5 in some lines becomes a target with White's g3-g4 and f2-f4.   If Black takes on f3 immediately, you have several options to choose from - recapture with the bishop and have flexible choices in the center (d2-d4 and c2-c4, or d2-d3 and e2-e4, or also d2-d3 and c2-c4), or play exf3 which I find to be the most interesting choice.} 
4. Bxf3 {If Black takes on f3 immediately, there's this interesting idea that I want to suggest.} 
5. exf3 {Of course, there's nothing wrong with capturing with the bishop and then trying to open the position for the bishop pair with something like c2-c4, or e2-e4, but this move is really idea-based and rather unpleasant for Black, especially if it comes as a surprise.} 
5. e5 {First, Black needs to understand that taking the center with two pawns not always is a good thing.} 
6. O-O
6. Bd6
7. d4 {White is ahead in development and now rips apart the center as you have a bishop who should control long and open diagonals.} 
7. Ne7
8. dxe5
8. Bxe5
9. f4
9. Bf6
10. c4 {Very energetical - the power of the light-squared bishop increases. The threat is to take on d5 and follow with Nc3.} 
10. dxc4
11. Nd2 {White already is better, willing to sacrifice a pawn if he has to, just to open more lines and more diagonals. Black already needs to be pretty careful.11...c3??A pawn is pawn, right?12.bxc3Bxc313.Rb1b614.Ne4Qxd115.Rxd1There are way too many threats for Black to handle - in such situations, an extra pawn means nothing.} 
