8. f4
8. Bd6 {A logical idea as Black also keeps an option at some point later to play ...e6-e5.8...g6I already mentioned that while I was writing the course, I was practicing a lot of additional King's Indian attack games, with both colors. In January of 2023, I happened to play this variation against Chess.com's latest sensation, the innocent-looking cat Mittens (a chess bot). Watch the model game to find out the outcome!} 
9. Nd2
9. O-O
10. Nf3
10. a5 {While this maneuver in the position is quite common to fight for the space advantage at the queenside, the real question that Black needs to answer - is to push ...e6-e5 or not. If he does it, the position opens and White simply enjoys a slightly better position due to the bishop pair. Remember the early choice to take on f3 with the e-pawn and not the bishop? Already then you were thinking, about how to improve the light-squared bishop power later in the game. Here it's already becoming stronger as Black weakens the control of the center.} 
11. a4 {You can also ignore the a-pawn's march but I think that in general, it doesn't hurt to fight for space advantage when you can.} 
11. Qc7
12. Re1
12. Rfe8
13. Be3
13. Re7
14. c3 {All of these moves are pretty common for the position. If Black wants to have some counterplay, he has to push ...e6-e5 now, accepting a slightly worse position.14...Rae8Here's how the game continued.15.d4!Change of the scenery - with a2-a4 and ...a7-a5 included, now Black can't easily seek the counterplay with ...c6-c5 as the b5 square would be weakened for good. Think about moving there your knight or even the light-squared bishop! This move was already available a move before.(15...c5?!16.Bf1!c417.b3White is dominating at the queenside).15...Nb6This is how the game continued.16.Ne5Nfd717.b3White's pressure is building up.17...f618.Ra2Na819.Nd3Nab620.Rae2White's advantage was quite large in Neiksans, A (2627) - Chabanon, J (2452) FRA-chT Top 12 2016.} 
