7. e5 {The most logical move - Black also can be ambitious.} 
8. e4
8. dxe4 {The safe move - Black closes the center to avoid any potential x-ray problems from the white queen, which conveniently stands on the same file as the black king.8...Bd6It's rather rare but a perfectly playable choice - Black could keep the tension in the center, at least for a while.9.Nh4O-OThe only move, otherwise White'sNf5could be a big problem.10.Nc3And now Black has to take on e4 anyway as closing the center with10...d4would give White a dream King's Indian attack scenario at the kingside. White reserves the option to capture on e4 also with the pieces to keep the light-squared bishop on g2 active - your choice.} 
9. dxe4 {Now it depends on what Black does. If he develops the dark-squared bishop on e7, then it's best to develop your queenside knight via d2 to c4 and strengthen it with a2-a4. The kingside knight can be activated via h4-f5, while also not forgetting about the aggressive f2-f4 pawn push.} 
9. Bc5 {For some there might be an argument - why develop the bishop humbly on e7 when it stands so active on c5? In reality, it's not so simple as now it's subject to losing a tempo.} 
10. a4 {A move that you will see a lot - White gains space at the queenside, and sometimes just stops Black's counter-attack with ...a7-a5-a4.} 
10. O-O {At some point, Black can consider taking on f3, aiming for a position with two knights as the light-squared bishop on h5 theoretically can either get into trouble or just do nothing as it's sort of locked out of the game. But again, let's remember why we included the early h2-h3 move! If Black takes on f3 after already having retreated to h5, he acknowledges the tempo loss which always is pleasant.} 
11. Nbd2
11. Re8
12. Nb3
12. Bf8
13. Nh4 {These maneuvers are quite common - the kingside knight is heading to f5, while the dark-squared bishop is to e3. There's no real advantage for White - just a nice positional game.} 
13. Qc7
14. Be3 {Consider locking out Black's light-squared bishop with an eventual f2-f3.14...a5Here's one high-level GM game which continued in the following way.15.f3This maneuver opens room for maneuvers like Qf2 and Rfd1, or Rf2-d2, or Bf2-Nf5-e3.15...b516.Qf2b4?Black thought that he will manage to push ...c6-c5-c4 later but he miscalculated.17.Nd2c518.b3Nb619.f4!This maneuver we already recognize - the black bishop on h5 is in danger.19...exf420.Bxf4Here it's stronger than capturing with the pawn as it comes with a tempo. It might not always be the case in similar circumstances.20...Qa721.e5Nfd522.Ne4White had a dominating position in Efimenko, Z (2635) - Timman, J (2541) Bundesliga 2018.} 
