1. e4 {1.Nf3The Reti variation players can get here with this order of the moves.1...d52.g3c6I already mentioned this in the previous chapter.3.Bg2g6Not among the most popular moves but it's a fairly reasonable idea.4.d3Bg75.Nbd2Transposing to the variations, covered in this chapter.} 
1. c6 {In the final chapter, I'd like to address another very popular defense from Black which is Caro-Kann. This will be more suitable for1.e4players but there's a fair chance that also the1.Nf3players will get there!} 
2. d3 {This order of the moves to reach the King's Indian attack positions is more popular and thus more played, however, there's one major drawback with the plan.} 
2. d5 {If we step back a move, Black doesn't have to play2...d5. He might even play2...e5and ...Nf6 to follow with a simple game.} 
3. Nd2
3. e5 {This is the strongest plan that Black can choose and it is pretty well known.} 
4. Ngf3
4. Bd6 {Depending on what White does next, Black will develop the kingside knight on f6 or e7 while keeping the tension in the center.} 
5. g3 {White can steer the game into King's Indian attack.5.d4This odd move almost by force reaches a position where Black has an IQP (isolated queen's pawn) position but Black's play is pretty simple and quite active.  It's a good idea to know this trick though as perhaps you can still do the same idea in better circumstances.5...exd46.exd5cxd57.Bb5+Nc68.Nxd4White is dreaming of a scenario to exploit the weak pawn on d5 and also enjoy the benefits of the outpost ond4but it's too little to claim any advantage.  It's Black who can easily organize an initiative at the kingside with typical ...Nf6, ...Bg4, and later the battery ...Bc7 Qd6 to follow.} 
5. Nf6
6. Bg2
6. O-O
7. O-O
7. Re8 {So far Black's game is simple, and so is White's. The main problem is that Black doesn't force things in the center, keeping the tension. If Black would take on e4, then we would reach some of the typical positions of King's Indian attack.   If Black closes the center, then White can start a kingside attack with the eventual f2-f4-f5. However, if Black is smart, he will postpone the decision until White reveals his cards.} 
8. b3 {Quite a popular choice to fianchetto the bishop.} 
8. a5
9. a3 {Or9.a4- Black's a-pawn march has to be stopped. The more modest9.a3keeps control of the b4 square.} 
9. Nbd7
10. Bb2
10. dxe4 {One of the simplest choices for Black but also closing the center with10...d4makes perfect sense, now that White's incoming f2-f4 will feel weaker with the dark-squared bishop on b2.} 
11. Nxe4
11. Nxe4
12. dxe4
12. Qc7 {The position is pretty peaceful with about equal chances.} 
