1. e4 {1.Nf3The Reti variation players can get here with this order of the moves.1...d52.g3c6I already mentioned this in the previous chapter.3.Bg2g6Not among the most popular moves but it's a fairly reasonable idea.4.d3Bg75.Nbd2Transposing to the variations, covered in this chapter.} 
1. c6 {In the final chapter, I'd like to address another very popular defense from Black which is Caro-Kann. This will be more suitable for1.e4players but there's a fair chance that also the1.Nf3players will get there!} 
2. Nf3 {Recently I've got quite fond of this move specifically against the Caro-Kann and what makes it better, it fits in the King's Indian attack schemes! I like it much more than the immediate2.d3as it forces Black's hand to play2...d5as other alternatives look less inspiring.} 
2. d5
3. d3 {I think this is a pretty smart order of the moves to avoid one of the best setups that Black can choose against King's Indian attack. Also, White doesn't mind trading queens.} 
3. dxe4 {Very tempting but it might not be the best.} 
4. dxe4
4. Qxd1+
5. Kxd1 {At the first sight it seems that Black has achieved more - he has no weaknesses while the white king can never castle. However, if you look more closely at the position, you'll realize that the king actually will feel wonderful on c2! Also, one of White's further ideas is to remove the knight from f3 with f2-f3 to follow, thus cementing the situation at the kingside, while leaving all the queenside at your disposal.} 
5. Bg4
6. Nbd2 {Black wants to ruin your pawn structure, so it makes sense to stop him.6.Be2It makes sense also to start with this move and Ne1 to follow.6...Nd77.Ne1Bxe2+8.Kxe2White's position seems simply more pleasant.} 
6. g6
7. c3
7. Bg7
8. Kc2
8. Nd7
9. Ne1 {A common maneuver in the line - White will play f2-f3 next.} 
9. Nb6
10. a4 {Seeking space and targets at the queenside.} 
10. a5
11. Nc4
11. Nxc4
12. Bxc4
12. Nf6
13. f3 {It seems that Black has done nothing wrong and yet his position deteriorates very quickly. Landing with the bishop on e6 will permanently damage Black's pawn structure.} 
13. Bd7
14. Nd3
14. b5 {Desperation but Black's position already is very difficult.} 
15. Bb3
15. O-O
16. Nc5
16. Bc8
17. Rd1 {White won the game due to the numerous Black's weaknesses at the queenside in Neiksans,A (2547)-Krilovs,N (2093) Latvian Team Rapid Championship 2022.} 
