9. O-O
9. Nbd7
10. Qe1 {A typical way to dodge the pin! Now you might remember something from the previous chapter - if Black develops the dark-squared bishop to c5, you can bother it with Nb3 and a2-a4. If Black doesn't do it, put the knight on c4 but prepare the maneuver with the a-pawn push.} 
10. Nc5
11. Nc4
11. Nfd7
12. b4 {Pay attention to this maneuver! With a2-a4 to follow, White gains a considerable space advantage at the queenside.} 
12. Ne6
13. a4 {White's position is better.13...f6For some reference we can follow a game, played about 50 years ago!14.c3Nb615.Nfd2The typical maneuver for the kingside knight - with the current pawn structure at the queenside, the white knight on c4 stands perfectly.15...Qf7?This was played in Panno, O-Kortschnoj, V Palma de Mallorca 1972. Black's last move was a positional mistake and White could have played a more direct continuation.16.Nxb6axb617.Nc4Black is behind in development and the pawn on b6 is terminally weak. Panno went on to win the game anyway.} 
