[White "4) Black's Caro-Kann"]
[Black "1.e4 c6 2.Nf3 d5 3.d3 Bg4 #1"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 {1.Nf3The Reti variation players can get here with this order of the moves.1...d52.g3c6I already mentioned this in the previous chapter.3.Bg2g6Not among the most popular moves but it's a fairly reasonable idea.4.d3Bg75.Nbd2Transposing to the variations, covered in this chapter.} 
1. c6 {In the final chapter, I'd like to address another very popular defense from Black which is Caro-Kann. This will be more suitable for1.e4players but there's a fair chance that also the1.Nf3players will get there!} 
2. Nf3 {Recently I've got quite fond of this move specifically against the Caro-Kann and what makes it better, it fits in the King's Indian attack schemes! I like it much more than the immediate2.d3as it forces Black's hand to play2...d5as other alternatives look less inspiring.} 
2. d5
3. d3 {I think this is a pretty smart order of the moves to avoid one of the best setups that Black can choose against King's Indian attack. Also, White doesn't mind trading queens.} 
3. Bg4 {A pretty standard response from a Caro-Kann player - the idea is to bring out the light-squared bishop and secure the position with ...e7-e6.3...Nf6?!While this seems to be a normal developing move, Black's problem lies with the fact that he's about to lose some tempos and White will simply gain a considerable space advantage.4.e5Nfd75.d4The common response - Black enters a worse version of the French defense where he has already committed to ...c7-c6. As you might know, Black usually seeks a counterplay at the queenside with ...c7-c5.5...e66.c4There might be other good moves as well - this one just discourages Black to continue with ...c6-c5 as Black's center would become quite shaky. White has a serious space advantage.} 
4. h3
4. Bh5 {If Black takes on f3, White takes with the queen and can progress with g2-g3 and Bg2, seeking to open the game for the light-squared bishop in the long-term. Intermezzo move 4...dxe4 is bad as after 5.hxg4 White will enjoy the extra benefits of the open h-file.} 
5. Nc3
5. d4 {That's a mistake, which I recently met myself against another GM.} 
6. g4 {A very strong intermezzo move as the following dynamics are in White's favor.} 
6. dxc3 {The actual game continued with a concession6...Bg67.Ne2where White obtained a large advantage with threats to win the d-pawn or push c2-c3 and Qb3 next, while Black’s light-squared bishop on g6 is excluded from the game. Neiksans, A - Akesson, R. Swedish Elitserien 2023.} 
7. gxh5
7. cxb2
8. Bxb2
8. Qa5+
9. Qd2 {Very strong! White sacrifices the h-pawn to accelerate his development.} 
9. Qxh5 {If Black trades the queens, White can recapture with the king.} 
10. Be2 {White’s lead in development is huge and probably is already strategically winning. Think about the next moves like Ne5, Qb4, and castle long.} 
