 {This typical pawn structure is very common for Chapter 1. While Black usually does play ...c7-c5 and ...Nc6, it's not mandatory. He might opt to go for a different plan, which usually is either ... b7-b6 and ...Bb7, or ...Nc6 with an idea to push ...e7-e5.} 1. dxe4 {It’s important to keep the central pawn. If White will take with the knight first, Black is not obliged to take on e4. Don’t worry about the knight on d2 which is blocking the dark-squared bishop – it will find a way to join the game.} 
2. dxe4
2. b6 {Depending on the order of the moves, Black normally wants either to stop White from playing e4 (it's already done here) or at least give his light-squared bishop a long diagonal.2...Nc6Depending on the situation, Black might develop the queenside knight without pushing forward the c-pawn. This signals that he wants to play ...e6-e5 next, fighting for the center.3.e5If you can, consider grabbing space advantage by pushing forward your e-pawn which not only stops Black's plan, but also opens your light-squared bishop on g2. It also gives White some opportunities for a potential kingside attack, like h2-h4 and Ng5 next. Of course, make sure that the e5 pawn itself doesn't become weak in the process. If Black's ...e6-e5 is unstoppable, you can challenge his central pawn with either b2-b3 and Bb2, or at some point Nc4.} 
3. e5
3. Nd5
4. a3 {White is threatening to win the knight with c2-c4.} 
