 {This is one of the most famous plans for Black in KIA. The idea is that before Black jumps with his knight from c6 to d4 (aiming for the f5 square) he waits until White commits to Ng4. Then after the trade, it's more difficult for White to attack the weakened d4 pawn, while Black is planning to storm the queenside, planning to exploit the weakened a3 pawn.   If the black knight jumps to d4 early, after the trade White can immediately challenge the pawn with moves like Qg4 and Nf3, combining the positional pressure with a kingside attack. If the white knight is already on g4, you can retreat with the knight to h2 and start the same plan. Or, toy with the order of the moves and postpone the knight's jump to g4 (if you can).} 1. Nf3 {White starts to pressure the d4 pawn. If Black is not careful, sometimes White can execute Bd2-b4.} 
1. Bc5
2. Ra2 {This weird move might be interesting for you to consider if the dark-squared bishop already stands on f4 – it keeps the control of the b2 square. Black’s task to crash through the queenside now is pretty difficult while White has free hands at the kingside.} 
