 {This scenario is quite unlikely to happen but still - normally you're not supposed to allow Black to close the center with both ...d5-d4 and ...e6-e5. If Black starts with ...e6-e5, you take on d5 and rip apart the center with moves like c2-c3 and d3-d4. If Black starts with ... d5-d4, you include e4-e5 to disrupt Black's plan and to continue your own typical KIA plans.   However, there's one particular order of the moves where Black can still achieve this type of position. If this happens, you can play the position as King's Indian with colors reversed.} 1. cxd4 {It’s important to take on d4 to generate some counterplay at the queenside. If you miss the right moment to capture the pawn, Black might take on c3 himself and create a nice target on d3.} 
1. cxd4
2. Bd2 {Think about activities at the queenside like b2-b4-b5 with a2-a4, or Nh4 and f2-f4. Black's strongest plan probably is to execute a well-planned ...b7-b5 to push away your knight and expand at the queenside.} 
