 {One of the standard pawn structures from Chapter 2 - Black fianchettoes the bishop on g7 to slow down your plan to push e4-e5, or at least immediately challenge the pawn. The black knight can stand either on f6 or e7. If it stands on f6, make sure that after e4-e5 and ...Nd7, the e5 pawn has enough support. Of course, push e4-e5 only after Black has castled short, otherwise Black might again surprise you with castling long and fighting for the center with ...h7-h6 and g6-g5.} 1. e5
1. h6
2. h4 {Black's ... g6-g5 plan should be stopped. If the black king is still in the center, Black might castle long and sacrifice the g-pawn to open both g and h-files. With the king already castled short, that seems to be very unlikely.} 
2. b6
3. N1h2 {The knight reaches some very nice targets from the g4 square.} 
3. Bb7 {3...h5This stops Ng4 but allows White to target Black's h-pawn.4.g4Depending on the position, White might be threatening with gxh5, Ng5 and Qxh5. It's wise to evaluate the current position if Black doesn't have a surprising counterstrike with ...f7-f6. White's g3-g4 breakthrough can also be prepared.} 
4. Ng4 {Even though Black can protect the h6 pawn with ...Nf6, the f6 square is terminally weak.} 
