 {Black appears to have some temporary initiative at the queenside, thus make sure you meet his plans accordingly. Black's kingside weaknesses are not going anywhere.} 1. Nb4
2. Bg5 {White's dark-squared bishop is a critical piece of the position as it controls most of the dark square weaknesses at the kingside - don't allow it to be traded for a knight. As long as you won't blunder some forks with ...Nc2 or ... Nd3, White's position should be preferred. White continues traditionally - h2-h4, Ne3(h2) to g4 and exploits those weaknesses. You can trade Black's active light-squared bishop with Bf1, which also opens a path for Kg2, Rh1 and h4-h5 attack. If you can, keep queens on the board.} 
