 {A standard position from Chapter 3 where Black is at crossroads. He faces a decision, which direction to take. While ... a7-a5 maneuver is common, he has to decide, where to develop the queenside knight - on d7 or a6. Also, Black might include ...dxe4 to open the light-squared bishop on h7. If this happens, White should adjust his plan.} 1. a5 {1...Nbd72.Qe2White might already push e4-e5 here but it can also wait – Black can’t really stop it and you might extract from your opponent another sub-optimal move and only then push the pawn2...a53.a4Once again, White stops Black's a-pawns marsh.3...Qb64.e5There’s not going to be a better time to push the e-pawn4...Ne85.Bh3White has closed the center to operate freely at the kingside. Black is supposed to seek some counterplay at the queenside but it's easier said than done. Sometimes the f3 knight can jump to d4.1...dxe42.dxe4Now that the pawn trade has been included, continuing with the e-pawn push could be risky as it would open Black's light-squared bishop. Best continue with Qe2 and depending on the availability, consider Ne5 with f2-f4 to follow. Perhaps there's room for an odd maneuver Ne1-d3 and the same f2-f4 plan.} 
2. a4 {Consider also2.a3which takes control of the b4 square but it might jump under Black's threat of ...c6-c5 and ...a5-a4, opening the queenside. Engines suggest the following idea - with the black knight on b8 play a2-a3 but after ...Nbd7, play a3-a4! Those are small nuances that might not be necessary but they are interesting.} 
2. Na6
3. Qe2 {Similar to a line before, White can delay the e-pawn push to extract something extra from Black, like an unnecessary ...Re8 move.} 
3. Nb4
4. Ne1 {The black knight on b4 is beautiful but White's plan at the kingside is very easy.} 
