 {If you have reached this position, you should be happy - Black's light-squared bishop on h5 is pretty passive. If Black would reach the same position with the light-squared bishop on c8, he should not move it to g4, which is a common inaccuracy in Italian Game and Ruy Lopez.   White wants to play a2-a4-a5 to grab some space at the queenside but first, Black needs to decide, where to position his dark-squared bishop. If he plays ...Bc5, then White's Nbd2-b3 with a4-a5 looks very strong. If the bishop goes to e7, White can develop the queenside knight to c4.   Consider locking out Black's light-squared bishop out of the game with moving away the knight to either d2 or h4 with f2-f3, or just trade it for the f3 knight.} 1. Bc5 {1...Be7A more cautious alternative but the bishop might have been developed here a couple moves before with a different order of the moves. Now the white knight goes to c42.Nbd2O-O3.Nc4Qc74.a4White slows down Black's ...b7-b5 which right here would cost him the control of the d5 square.4...Rfe85.Nh4Before defining the placement of the dark-squared bishop, it seems to be a better idea to improve the kingside knight first.5...Bg66.Nxg6hxg67.Be3White is pressing.} 
2. a4
2. O-O
3. Nbd2 {The standard square for the queenside knight – on c3 it’s not doing anything.} 
3. Re8
4. Nb3 {Black has difficulties finding a good square for the dark-squared bishop. If he would prepare a retreat on a7 with an earlier included ...a7-a6, White could fix a weakness on b6 with a4-a5. If Black would play ...a7-a5 first, then after Bd2 the pawn on a5 makes a fine target.} 
