 {One of the main structures from Chapter 4 - it depends, on who is to move. If White can push e4-e5 and start the kingside attack, go for it.} 1. e5 {1.a3If Black is to move (for this I'm including this useless move), he can and probably should fight for the center with ...e7-e5.1...e52.exd5Before Black can close the center for good, it's time to open it, increasing the power of White's light-squared bishop on g2.2...Bxf33.Nxf3Nxd5There might be a moment when Black can recapture with the c-pawn. If this happens, consider continuing with c2-c4 to further open the h1-a8 diagonal.4.h4White wants to provoke Black for some weaknesses. If the dark-squared bishop is already on d2, there might be an option to play c2-c4 and Bc3, pressuring the e5 pawn.} 
1. Ne8
